{"parentUuid":"170823e2-0bda-43a4-b8eb-27c416216ae2","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NY2iUs6VYCvC6daRdzu1yv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The skill files use shorthand model names: `opus`, `sonnet`, `haiku`. The Claude Code skill system maps these to the latest models in each tier. Looking at the system context:\n\n- `opus` → claude-opus-4-7\n- `sonnet` → claude-sonnet-4-6\n- `haiku` → claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\n\nThe shorthands are already the correct format for skill files - they automatically map to the latest model in that tier. The user wants to \"utilize the models recommended\", meaning the latest models in each tier.\n\n\nI'm realizing the current configuration already uses these shorthands, which means the skills are already mapped to the latest versions. The question is whether the user wants explicit full model IDs instead, or if there are specific skills that could be optimized to use a different tier for their particular task. I'm realizing the Agent tool definition only accepts the shorthand forms like \"sonnet\", \"opus\", and \"haiku\", and the SKILL.md files use these same shorthands. Let me look at what the dist-skills format actually uses to see if there's a pattern I'm missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3865,"cache_read_input_tokens":23478,"output_tokens":771,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3865,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":771,"cache_read_input_tokens":23478,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3865,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3865},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CaEybLW491dHbwiMHvn1K","type":"assistant","